AU, Ayala, EON Capital, HTC, Philex, Posco: Asia Ex-Japan Equity Preview

-- B y   I a n   C .   S a y s o n
-- 
2011-05-02T21:51:58Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-02/ayala-eon-capital-philex-posco-asia-ex-japan-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes today in Asian trading, excluding  Japan .
Stock symbols are in parentheses, and share prices are from the
previous close, unless noted otherwise.  AU Optronics Corp. (2409)  (2409 TT):  Taiwan ’s second-largest maker
of liquid-crystal displays, said it plans to invest $796.3
million in  China ’s Kunshan Longfei Optoelectronics Co. AU will
withdraw an earlier application to Taiwan’s government to set up
a panel unit in China because of this investment, the company
said in a Taiwan stock-exchange filing April 29. The stock sank
5 percent to NT$22.95 when it last traded on April 29.  Ayala Corp. (AC)  : The owner of the largest Philippine
developer said demand for its 10-year bond is estimated at more
than twice the 10-billion peso ($234 million) offered at a rate
of 6.8 percent. Ayala’s bond, which has put options on 2016 and
2019, will refinance its preferred “B” shares and will be sold
until May 6, the company said in an e-mailed statement. The
stock decreased 1.8 percent to 384 pesos.  EON Capital Bhd. (EON)  : EON accepted Hong Leong Bank
Bhd.’s (HLBK MK) 5.06 billion ringgit ($1.7 billion) takeover
offer for the Malaysian lender after the bid was sweetened with
a dividend payment to existing EON shareholders, according to a
company statement. EON accepted the bid on condition Hong Leong
had no objections to a 311.9 million ringgit dividend payout, it
said. Hong Leong said in a separate statement that it’s
“agreeable” to EON’s proposal. EON rose 0.7 percent to 7.23
ringgit before it was suspended. Hong Leong added 0.6 percent to
10.40 ringgit before its trading halt.  Hon Hai Precision Industry Co. (2317 TT): The world’s
largest contract maker of electronics posted a 20 percent drop
in quarterly profit after high wage rates and investment in new
factories increased costs. First-quarter net income fell to
NT$14.4 billion ($503 million) from NT$18 billion a year earlier,
the Taipei-based company said in an April 29 exchange filing.
The average of nine analyst estimates compiled by Bloomberg was
for profit of NT$16 billion. The stock decreased 0.5 percent to
NT$108.50 on April 29.  HTC Corp. (2498)  (2498 TT): The Taiwanese smartphone maker plans
to pay a 2010 cash dividend of NT$37 per share, and 50 shares
for each 1,000 currently held, the Taoyuan, Taiwan-based company
said in an exchange filing April 30. Separately, the company
will pay around NT$1.8 billion to buy approximately 48,975
square meters adjacent to its current headquarters, it said. The
stock was unchanged at NT$1,300 on April 29.  Philex Mining Corp. (PX)  : The largest Philippine metals
producer had its 12-month share-price estimate increased to
26.80 pesos from 16.95 pesos at Philippine Equity Partners Inc.
The stock’s “buy” rating was maintained, according to the
Manila-based brokerage. The stock climbed 3.5 percent to 18.42
pesos.  Posco (005490)  (005490 KS):  South Korea ’s largest steelmaker expects
to renew in the next 10 days an accord with Orissa’s government
for building a $12 billion steel complex in the eastern state,
Vikas Sharan, vice president of the company’s Indian operations,
said in a telephone interview yesterday. The stock rose 1.3
percent to 474,000 won.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Ian C. Sayson in Manila at 
 isayson@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
